                  "__cdata": "<p class=\"p_20 black\">Correct!</p><p>Correct answer is C : Scrotal ultrasonography<br/><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">Ultrasound remains the mainstay in scrotal imaging not only because of its high accuracy, </strong>excellent depiction of scrotal anatomy, low cost and wide availability, it is also useful in determining whether a mass is intra- or extra-testicular. However, physicians should remember to first use simple transillumination tests for such a differential diagnosis. fluid collection within the vaginal sac transilluminates while testicular mass does not. CT scan for staging to know the spread of disease.</p><p><br></p><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(153, 51, 255);\">Tumor markers-LDh AFP and HCG are adjunct to the diagnosis and subsequent management of testicular neoplasm</strong>. needle biopsy may be used in Azoospermia related to infertility problems Inguinal Orchiectomy-is performed once ultrasound has established that scrotal enlargement is caused by an intratesticular tumour.</p>.</p>"
