            "__cdata": "<p class=\"p_20\">34. A 74-year-old man complains of lower abdominal pain. He has become aware of a periumbilical mass during that time. His past medical history is significant for hypertension and type 2 diabetes. He has a history of diverticulitis 1 year ago. On physical examination, he is afebrile and appears mildly uncomfortable. On abdominal examination, there is a palpable <br />\nmass extending from the pubic ramus to the umbilicus with a smooth contour. Laboratory results reveal a BUN of 14 mg/dL and a creatinine of 1.8 mg/dL. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient?</p>"
